clinical_study.brief_title: Safety and Tolerability of AGN-199201 in Patients With Erythema Associated With Rosacea

brief_summary.textblock: This study will evaluate the safety and tolerability of AGN-199201 for the treatment of erythema associated with rosacea.

primary_outcome.measure: Percentage of Responders With at Least a 2-Grade Decrease From Baseline in Both Clinician Erythema Assessment (CEA) and Subject's Self Assessment (SSA) at Day 1
primary_outcome.description: The percentage of responders was determined by facial sides with at least a 2-grade decrease from Baseline (Improvement) in the CEA score and at least a 2-grade decrease from Baseline (Improvement) in the SSA score at Day 1. The investigator evaluated the severity of the participant's erythema (redness of the skin) as measured by the CEA using a 5-point scale where 0=clear skin with no signs of erythema; 1=almost clear of erythema, slight redness; 2=mild erythema, definite redness; 3=moderate erythema, marked redness and 4=severe erythema, fiery redness. The participant assessed the severity of their erythema as measured by the SSA using a 5-point scale where 0=clear of unwanted redness; 1=nearly clear of unwanted redness; 2=somewhat more redness than I prefer; 3=more redness than I prefer and 4=completely unacceptable redness.

criteria.textblock:
Inclusion Criteria:
- facial erythema associated with rosacea on both sides of the face
Exclusion Criteria:
- Laser light-source or other energy based therapy in the last 6 months
- Excessive hair around the treatment area

outcome.description: The percentage of responders was determined by facial sides with at least a 2-grade decrease from Baseline (Improvement) in the CEA score and at least a 2-grade decrease from Baseline (Improvement) in the SSA score at Day 1. certain_agreements.restrictive_agreement: A disclosure restriction on the PI is that the sponsor can review results communications prior to public release and can embargo communications regarding trial results for a period that is less than or equal to 90 days from the time submitted to the sponsor for review.
